{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17539375","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17539375"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:40:34+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:40:34+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16591"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16591","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16591"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.16,0.34,0.32,0.07,0.12]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9282"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104514"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9282","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9282"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16591"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86841"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"73"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1219"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"7938"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21989"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35633"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35652"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104514","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/104514"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 30-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a six-month history of painful lumps on his scalp. The lesions started as tender nodules that would occasionally drain purulent material. He reports similar episodes over the past two years and has some patch hair loss from these episodes. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. He works as an accountant and reports feeling increasingly self-conscious about his appearance.  He is needle-phobic.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There are multiple boggy, tender nodules, keloids and sinus tracts on his scalp. Several areas show scarring and hair loss. There are no lesions elsewhere on his body.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate treatment?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Incision and drainage of lesions","Oral isotretinoin","Topical clindamycin","Zinc supplementation","Oral prednisolone"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classic features of dissecting cellulitis of the scalp (also known as perifolliculitis capitis), a rare chronic inflammatory condition characterised by painful nodules, interconnecting sinus tracts, purulent discharge and progressive scarring alopecia. The condition predominantly affects young men of African descent and can have significant physical and psychological impact. Initial treatment can be with oral antibiotics for anti-inflammatory properties and intralesional corticosteroids however this patient already as keloids and patch alopecia and thus has moderate disease requiring stronger treatment. The cause of the disease is unknown and it has a relapsing, life-long course that requires careful management to reduce alopecia and the psychological impact.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral isotretinoin\u003C/strong\u003E is the most effective medical therapy for moderate to severe dissecting cellulitis. It works by reducing sebum production and has anti-inflammatory properties. A typical course lasts 4-6 months, with many patients achieving long-term remission. Regular monitoring of liver function and lipids is required.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETopical clindamycin\u003C/strong\u003E alone would be insufficient for this severity of disease. While it may help with superficial bacterial colonisation, it cannot penetrate deeply enough to address the underlying inflammatory process.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral prednisolone\u003C/strong\u003E might provide temporary relief but is not appropriate for long-term management due to side effects. Additionally, symptoms typically recur once steroids are discontinued.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncision and drainage\u003C/strong\u003E is not recommended as a primary treatment as it may worsen scarring and does not address the underlying pathology. It may also promote the formation of new sinus tracts.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EZinc supplementation\u003C/strong\u003E has no proven benefit in dissecting cellulitis of the scalp. While zinc may have a role in some inflammatory skin conditions, it is not an evidence-based treatment for this condition.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Oral isotretinoin is the most effective medical therapy for moderate to severe dissecting cellulitis of the scalp."],"references":["DermNet New Zealand. Scalp folliculitis [Internet]. Reviewed and updated by Dr Amanda Oakley, Dermatologist, Hamilton, New Zealand; Vanessa Ngan, Staff Writer; Clare Morrison, Copy Editor, June 2014. Available at: https://dermnetnz.org/topics/scalp-folliculitis","Australian College of Dermatologists. Dissecting cellulitis of the scalp [Internet]. Sydney: ACD. Available at: https://www.dermcoll.edu.au/atoz/dissecting-cellulitis-scalp/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86841"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16591"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86841","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/86841"},"attribute